\title{
\textbf{On the Negligible Influence of Gravitational-Wave Backscatter on Late-Time Growth}\\[0.5em]
\large A Conservative Bound from Effective Stress-Energy Considerations
}
\author{Andrew Michael Brilliant\\
Independent Researcher, Sapporo, Japan\\
\texttt{a.brilliant@ieee.org}}

\date{August 23, 2016}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
In the short-wavelength regime where Isaacson averaging applies, a stochastic gravitational wave background admits an effective stress--energy tensor and behaves as an additional radiation component with equation of state $w=1/3$.  
This note provides a conservative bound on the impact such a component can have on late-time structure growth through its contribution to the background expansion and scalar-sector sourcing.

The result is intended as a bookkeeping constraint for cosmological analyses rather than a claim of new physical effects.  Under standard assumptions, any contribution to the logarithmic growth rate satisfies
\[
\left|\Delta f / f\right| \lesssim C\,\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}},
\]
where $\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}}$ is the total gravitational-wave energy density and $C$ is an order-unity factor encapsulating conservative modeling choices.  Using current bounds on extra radiation energy density, this implies a ceiling of order $\mathrm{few}\times 10^{-4}$, well below the sensitivity of present large-scale structure measurements.
\end{abstract}

\section{Purpose and scope}

This note is intended as a compact reference for bounding the influence of a stochastic gravitational-wave background on late-time cosmological growth through its effective stress energy.
It is not a proposal for new physics, nor an attempt to identify observable signatures beyond existing constraints.

The focus is strictly on the regime where Isaacson averaging applies, i.e.\ when gravitational wavelengths are much shorter than the background curvature scale.  
Effects arising from horizon-scale tensor modes, nonperturbative backreaction, or modified gravity are outside the scope of this note.

\section{Effective stress energy in the short-wavelength regime}

We decompose the spacetime metric as
\begin{equation}
g_{\mu\nu} = \bar{g}_{\mu\nu} + h_{\mu\nu},
\end{equation}
with $\bar{g}_{\mu\nu}$ a smooth FLRW background and $h_{\mu\nu}$ a rapidly varying tensor perturbation.

Following Isaacson \citep{Isaacson1968a,Isaacson1968b}, averaging over scales large compared to the wavelength but small compared to the curvature radius yields an effective stress--energy tensor
\begin{equation}
T^{\mathrm{GW}}_{\mu\nu}
= -\frac{1}{8\pi G}
\left\langle G^{(2)}_{\mu\nu}[h,h;\bar{g}] \right\rangle .
\end{equation}

In transverse–traceless gauge this reduces to
\begin{equation}
T^{\mathrm{GW}}_{\mu\nu}
= \frac{1}{32\pi G}
\left\langle
\nabla_\mu h^{\mathrm{TT}}_{\alpha\beta}
\nabla_\nu h^{\mathrm{TT}\,\alpha\beta}
\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}
which corresponds to an effective radiation fluid with equation of state $w=1/3$.

\section{Impact on background expansion and growth}

The background Friedmann equation becomes
\begin{equation}
3H^2 = 8\pi G \left( \rho + \rho_{\mathrm{GW}} \right),
\end{equation}
so that the fractional change in the expansion rate satisfies
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta H^2}{H^2} \sim \Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}} .
\end{equation}

At the level of linear perturbations, the growth factor $D(a)$ obeys
\begin{equation}
\delta'' + \left(2 + \frac{H'}{H}\right)\delta' - \frac{3}{2}\Omega_m(a)\,\delta = \text{sources},
\end{equation}
where primes denote derivatives with respect to $\ln a$.
To leading order, any modification entering solely through the background or averaged stress energy produces corrections proportional to $\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}}$.

We therefore write the conservative bound
\begin{equation}
\boxed{
\left|\frac{\Delta f}{f}\right| \lesssim C\,\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}}
}
\end{equation}
with $C$ an $\mathcal{O}(1$–$10)$ factor accounting for uncertainties in averaging and mode coupling.

\section{Numerical bound from radiation constraints}

Constraints on additional relativistic energy density are commonly expressed as bounds on $\Delta N_{\mathrm{eff}}$.
Using
\begin{equation}
\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}} h^2
\simeq
\left(\frac{7}{8}\right)
\left(\frac{4}{11}\right)^{4/3}
\Omega_\gamma h^2\,\Delta N_{\mathrm{eff}},
\end{equation}
and current limits $\Delta N_{\mathrm{eff}} \lesssim 0.4$, one obtains
\begin{equation}
\Omega_{\mathrm{GW}}^{\mathrm{tot}} \lesssim \mathcal{O}(10^{-5}),
\end{equation}
implying
\begin{equation}
\left|\frac{\Delta f}{f}\right| \lesssim \mathrm{few}\times 10^{-4}
\end{equation}
even under deliberately conservative assumptions.

\section{Scope and limitations}

This bound applies only within the Isaacson short-wavelength regime and only to effects entering through the averaged stress--energy tensor.
It does not constrain direct tensor observables, horizon-scale effects, or modified gravity scenarios in which the mapping between tensor perturbations and effective stress energy is altered.

\section{Conclusion}

Within its regime of validity, the Isaacson effective stress energy of a stochastic gravitational-wave background produces a strictly bounded and negligibly small contribution to late-time structure growth.
The result is intended as a practical reference point for error budgeting rather than as evidence for new physics.

\section*{Acknowledgment}

This note is intended as a technical record for future reference and reproducibility.

